<div class="body" id="fhbody-174415177">
	
		
	

	
		
		<div id="text-174415177" class="p">
			
		 	
				Microsoft told employees in China that from September <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-07-08/microsoft-orders-china-staff-to-switch-from-android-phones-to-iphones-for-work">they'll only be able to use iPhones for work</a>, effectively cutting off Android-powered devices from the workplace. Bloomberg:<i> The US company will soon require Chinese-based employees to use only Apple devices to verify their identities when logging in to work computers or phones, according to an internal memo reviewed by Bloomberg News. The measure, part of Microsoft's global Secure Future Initiative, will affect hundreds of workers across the Chinese mainland and is intended to ensure that all staff use the Microsoft Authenticator password manager and Identity Pass app.<br> <br>

The move highlights the fragmented nature of Android app stores in the country and the growing differences between Chinese and foreign mobile ecosystems. Unlike Apple's iOS store, Google Play isn't available in China, so local smartphone makers like Huawei and Xiaomi operate their own platforms. Microsoft has chosen to block access from those devices to its corporate resources because they lack Google's mobile services in the country, the message said.</i><br>
		 	
		</div>

		

		

		
			
		
	</div>
